{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:06:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:06:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2073"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2073"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.53,0.11,0.21,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2073"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71318"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2955"},{"type":"tags","id":"2966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"90"},{"type":"contributions","id":"91"},{"type":"contributions","id":"92"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42452"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of increased urination and excessive thirst. He reports drinking 10-15 cups of water daily but still feels extremely thirsty. He complains of disrupted sleep due to frequent urination at night. He has a medical history of bipolar disorder. His only regular medication is lithium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He is alert and oriented to time, place, and person. There is loss of skin turgor, and his mucous membranes appear dry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum sodium: 151 mmol/L (137-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 4.5 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlasma osmolality: 290 mOsm/kg H2O (275-295)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine osmolality: 130 mOsm/kg H2O (500-850)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntidiuretic hormone (ADH): Elevated\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psychogenic polydipsia","Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","Central diabetes insipidus","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion","Chronic kidney disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and laboratory findings consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Enephrogenic diabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E, most likely induced by chronic lithium use. Lithium, a first-line agent for bipolar disorder, is a common cause of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus as it reduces the kidney\u0027s ability to respond to antidiuretic hormone (ADH).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic polydipsia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by compulsive, excessive water drinking behaviour commonly associated with psychiatric disorders. While it can cause polyuria, patients typically do not show signs of dehydration as seen in this case. Additionally, urine osmolality would be low, but serum sodium and osmolality would typically be normal or low, unlike the elevated levels seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral diabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by insufficient ADH production, often due to pituitary dysfunction. However, this would result in decreased ADH levels, contrary to the elevated ADH levels observed in this patient. Central diabetes insipidus is characterized by low ADH production, whereas nephrogenic diabetes insipidus (as seen here) involves normal or elevated ADH levels with kidney resistance to its effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH)\u003C/strong\u003E presents with decreased urinary frequency and volume, hyponatraemia, and concentrated urine. This is inconsistent with the polyuria, hypernatraemia, and dilute urine seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with polyuria in its early stages, but would typically be associated with other biochemical abnormalities such as elevated creatinine and urea. Additionally, the ability to concentrate urine is usually preserved until late stages of chronic kidney disease. The pattern of elevated ADH with dilute urine is more consistent with nephrogenic diabetes insipidus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic use of lithium is an important cause of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus.","Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus is characterised by elevated ADH levels with low urine osmolality and high serum sodium.","Differentiating between central and nephrogenic diabetes insipidus involves assessing ADH levels and response to desmopressin."],"references":["Boton R, Gaviria M, Batlle D. Prevalence, Pathogenesis, and Treatment of Renal Dysfunction Associated With Chronic Lithium Therapy. American Journal of Kidney Diseases. 1987;10(5):329-345. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3314489/","Gr\u00fcnfeld J, Rossier B. Lithium nephrotoxicity revisited. Nature Reviews Nephrology. 2009;5(5):270-276. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19384328/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71318"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2073"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71318"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T20:23:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T11:53:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2073"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh